	                    <div class="dsq-avatar dsq-tt">
	                        <a href="https://disqus.com/by/weaverryan/">
	                            	                                <img alt="" src="http://a.disquscdn.com/uploads/users/32/6480/avatar92.jpg?1482356913">
	                            	                        </a>
	                    </div>
	                    <div class="dsq-comment-body" id="dsq-comment-body-2965663649">
	                        <div class="dsq-comment-header">
	                            <span class="dsq-comment-date">2016-10-24</span>
	                            <span class="dsq-commenter-name">weaverryan</span>
	                        </div>

	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-2965663649" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-2965663649" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Yo Max!</p><p>You found the flexibility of PHP! This does work... but I wouldn't do it on purpose :) - mostly because it is kind of "unexpected" (like, wait, why is he/she doing that? Is something fancy happening here!?). The key thing is that constants are *static* - they're a "thing" that's attached to the *class* (e.g. ClassName) itself - it is not something that's attached to your object. When you use $this::CONST (you can also have $someObj::CONST) it makes it kind of look like the constant is somehow attached to the object instead of the class.</p><p>But, I like that you're poking at things to see if they work - all good for learning :).</p><p>Cheers!</p>
	                            </div>
	                        </div>
	                    </div>
	                </li>
	            	                <li class="dsq-comment dsq-clearfix" data-dsq-comment-id="2964595586" id="dsq-comment-2964595586">
